abstract:
Hypergroups [\textit{F. Marty}, in: 8. Skand. Mat. Kongr., Stockholm,45--49 (1934; JFM 61.1014.03)] are a generalization of groups that allow for the product of two elements to be a nonempty set of elements, while hyperrings and hyperfields [Zbl 0085.26501, \S 3] are ring-like objects whose additive structure is a particular kind of hypergroup. This paper aims to analyze hypergroups and related structures within a categorical context.

The paper considers the following categories
\[
\begin{array} [c]{ccccccc} \mathsf{cMsc} & \subset & \mathsf{Msc} & \subset & \mathsf{uHMag} & \hookrightarrow & \mathsf{HMag}\\
\cup & & \cup & & \cup & & \\
\mathsf{Can} & \subset & \mathsf{HGrp} & \subset & \mathsf{HMon} & & \\
\cup & & \cup & & \cup & & \\
\mathsf{Ab} & \subset & \mathsf{Grp} & \subset & \mathsf{Mon} & & \end{array}
\]
where

\begin{itemize}
\item \(\mathsf{HMag}\) and \(\mathsf{uHMag}\)\ are the categories of hypermagmas [\textit{A. Dudzik}, ``Quantales and hyperstructures: monads, Mo' problems'', Preprint, \url{arXiv:1707.09227}] and unital hypermagmas;

\item \(\mathsf{Msc}\) and \(\mathsf{cMsc}\)\ are the categories of mosaics and commutative mosaics;

\item \(\mathsf{HGrp}\), \(\mathsf{Can}\)\ and \(\mathsf{HMon}\)\ are the categories of hypergroups, canonical hypergroups and hypermonoids;

\item \(\mathsf{Mon}\), \(\mathsf{Grp}\)\ and \(\mathsf{Ab}\)\ denote the usual categories of monoids, groups and abelian groups.
\end{itemize}

It is shown that the categories \(\mathsf{HMag}\), \(\mathsf{uHMag}\)\ and \(\mathsf{Msc}\) are complete and cocomplete, while the categories of hypergroups and canoical hypergroups fail to be either complete or cocomplete. The various epimorphisms and monomorphisms are characterized in the categories \(\mathsf{HMag}\), \(\mathsf{uHMag}\), \(\mathsf{Msc}\)\ and \(\mathsf{cMsc}\). It turns out that the categories \(\mathsf{HMag}\), \(\mathsf{uHMag}\)\ and \(\mathsf{cMsc}\) are of closed monoidal structures. The following two theorems are established in the final section (\S 4).

Theorem. The categories of multirings and hyperrings have fully faithful embeddings into the category of monoid objects in \(\mathsf{cMsc}\).

Theorem. There is a faithful functor
\[
\mathsf{sMat}_{\cdot}\rightarrow\mathsf{cMsc}
\]
from the category of simple pointed matroids to \(\mathsf{cMsc}\). This functor induces a fully faithful embedding of projective geometries into commutative mosaics.
